ce:section.ce:para:
MIPs were synthesized via a modified precipitation polymerization method (Gao et al., 2015). In brief, 0.26 mmol of histamine (template) was dissolved into 40 mL of acetonitrile (porogen) and mixed with 1.3 mmol of MAA (functional monomer) in a 100-mL round-bottomed flask. The mixture was magnetically stirred for 30 min to ensure adequate reaction between the template and functional monomer. Then, 6.56 mmol of EGDMA (cross-linker) and 20 mg AIBN (initiator) were introduced. The mixture was purged with nitrogen for 5 min and incubated at 55 °C for 24 h in an oil bath. The resultant polymers were washed manually under sonication with methanol-acetic acid (90:10, v/v) to remove the template, followed by using pure methanol for further extraction (
                           Fig. S1
                        ). Finally, the MIPs were vacuum dried at 40 °C for 12 h. The non-imprinted polymers (NIPs) were synthesized in the same manner without the addition of the template (i.e., histamine).

A total of 20 mg MIPs was weighed into a 2-mL microcentrifuge tube as the sorbent for dSPE. The recovery rates of MIPs towards histamine standard solution were determined to be 95.22 ± 2.6 %, 93.33 ± 3.6 %, and 93.50 ± 4.4 % at 5 ppm, 30 ppm, and 100 ppm, respectively. In comparison, the corresponding recovery rates of NIPs were determined to be 64.00 ± 2.3 %, 43.17 ± 1.6 %, and 39.50 ± 2.7 %. Recovery of histamine from canned tuna during sample preparation was then evaluated. Tuna samples were first spiked with histamine to different levels (i.e., 5, 30, 100 mg/kg), followed by a simple pre-treatment of extraction. The pre-treated canned tuna extract was then loaded into the microcentrifuge tube to perform MI-dSPE. The recovery rates of histamine in canned tuna after sample preparation ranged from 91.91 % to 94.41 % with the relative standard deviation of 2.7 %-3.8 % (
                           Table S1
                        ).
